Among the options, only insulin antagonism of human placental lactogen contributes to the pathogenesis of gestational diabetes, as this hormone reduces insulin sensitivity. Autoantibodies against pancreatic beta cells are associated with type 1 diabetes, point mutations in the gene coding for insulin are associated with monogenic diabetes, and decrease in insulin gene expression is associated with type 2 diabetes.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient is presenting with gestational diabetes, which is caused by insulin resistance due to hormones produced by the placenta, including human placental lactogen. Autoantibodies against pancreatic beta cells and point mutations in the gene coding for insulin are more commonly associated with type 1 diabetes, while a decrease in insulin gene expression can lead to type 2 diabetes.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient’s condition is gestational diabetes mellitus (GDM). Insulin antagonism of human placental lactogen (HPL) is the leading hypothesis of GDM pathogenesis. HPL is a hormone produced by the placenta during pregnancy, which has a structural similarity to growth hormone and prolactin. It is well established that HPL has an insulin-antagonistic effect, and it is thought that high HPL levels in GDM lead to insulin resistance. Autoantibodies against pancreatic beta cells and point mutations in the insulin gene are common causes of type 1 diabetes, which is not the same as GDM. Decrease in insulin gene expression is not implicated in GDM pathogenesis.

Autoantibodies against pancreatic beta cells are associated with Type 1 diabetes, point mutations in the gene coding for insulin are associated with rare forms of diabetes, and decrease in insulin gene expression is associated with Type 2 diabetes, but none of these are relevant to the pathogenesis of gestational diabetes.
